<span id="freeTextContainer12599120714855502564"><i>&quot;Many-formed are the gods; and the end men look for is not the end they bring.&quot;</i><br/>- Mary Renault, The King Must Die<br/><br/> <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1531809120i/25984789._SX540_.jpg' width='400' height='268' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>A nice, detailed historical fiction (well, let&apos;s call it mytholigical fiction, yes?) about Theseus, the founding hero of Athens. Renault takes many of the Labors of Theseus and weaves them with the stories of Theseus, Aegeus, and Medea, and Theseus, King Minos, and the Minotaur.<br/><br/>Structurally, it reminded me a bit of Knausgaard&apos;s book &apos;A Time For Everything&apos; where he takes the flood myt</span>
  <span id="freeText12599120714855502564" style="display:none"><i>"Many-formed are the gods; and the end men look for is not the end they bring."</i><br>- Mary Renault, The King Must Die<br><br> <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1531809120i/25984789._SX540_.jpg" width="400" height="268" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>A nice, detailed historical fiction (well, let's call it mytholigical fiction, yes?) about Theseus, the founding hero of Athens. Renault takes many of the Labors of Theseus and weaves them with the stories of Theseus, Aegeus, and Medea, and Theseus, King Minos, and the Minotaur.<br><br>Structurally, it reminded me a bit of Knausgaard's book 'A Time For Everything' where he takes the flood myths of genesis and humanizes them. Both Mnausgaard and Renaut share the same gift for seeing the men (and women) behind the myth; of deconstructing what the history might have looked like that created these origin myths. I love this approach. It, at once, is interesting, informative, and subversive.</span>
